Here it is formatted so we can read it:

	public static string StripStringFormating(string formattedString)
	{
		if (rTest.IsMatch(formattedString))
			return rTest.Replace(formattedString, string.Empty);
		else
			return formattedString;
	}

	// #1
	static Regex rText = new Regex(@"\e\[[\d;]+m", RegexOptions.Compiled);
	// #2
	static Regex rTest = new Regex(@"(\e(\[([\d;]*[mz]?))?)?", RegexOptions.Compiled);

The reason why #1 is slower is that [\d;]+ is a greedy quantifier. Using +? or *? is going to do lazy quantifing. See [MSDN - Quantifiers][1] for more info.

You may want to try:

    "(\e\[(\d{1,2};)*?[mz]?)?"

That may be faster for you.

[1]:http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/3206d374(VS.80).aspx

